h$nindicates that they are drawn from the same population of early-type$\backslash$ngalaxies. LLRG represent only the tip of the iceberg associated with$\backslash$n(relatively) high activity levels, with CoreG forming the bulk of the$\backslash$npopulation. We do not find any relationship between radio-power and$\backslash$nblack hole mass. A minimum black hole mass of M{\_}BH = 108$\backslash$nMȯ is apparently associated with the radio-loud nuclei$\backslash$nin both CoreG and LLRG, but this effect must be tested on a sample of$\backslash$nless luminous galaxies, likely to host smaller black holes. In the$\backslash$nunifying model for BL Lacs and radio-galaxies, CoreG likely represent$\backslash$nthe counterparts of the large population of low luminosity BL Lac now$\backslash$nemerging from the surveys at low radio flux limits. This suggests the$\backslash$npresence of relativistic jets also in these quasi-quiescent early-type$\backslash$n"core" galaxies.},
